Time Model Statistics

  • DB Time represents total time in user calls
  • DB CPU represents CPU time of foreground processes
  • Total CPU Time represents foreground and background processes
  • Statistics including the word "background" measure background process time, therefore do not contribute to the DB time statistic
  • Ordered by % of DB time in descending order, followed by Statistic Name

IF "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.trace_level >= 0 THEN "FE_GG" .trace_put_line ('DDL', 'Start SCN found [' || to_char("FE_GG" .DDLReplication.SCNB + "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.SCNW * power (2, 32)) || ']'); END IF; -- restore module info dbms_application_info.set_module(oldModuleNameInfo, oldActionInfo); -- do not calculate/r ecord any metadata for objects other than table, index or trigger -- because these are the objects we need to resolve base owner/name for -- also do not calculate metadata for TRUNCATE TABLE -- because customer may have hundreds of those - they don't change table structure!!! IF (NOT real_ora_dict_obj_type = 'TABLE' AND NOT real_ora_dict_obj_type = 'INDEX' AND NOT real_ora_dict_obj_type = 'TRIGGER' AND NOT real_ora_dict_obj_type = 'SEQUENCE') OR (real_ora_dict_obj_type = 'TABLE' AND ora_sysevent = 'TRUNCATE') OR (real_ora_dict_obj_type = 'TRIGGER' AND ora_sysevent <> 'CREATE') OR "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.stay_metadata = 1 -- do not query db for metadata if STAYMETADATA is ON THEN IF "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.trace_level >= 0 THEN "FE_GG" .trace_put_line ('DDL', '------------------------- End of log for DDL sequence [' || to_ch ar ("FE_GG" .DDLReplication.currentDDLSeq) || '], no DDL history metadata recorded for this DDL operation'); END IF; IF "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.sql_trace = 1 THEN dbms_session.set_sql_trace(false); END IF; "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.setCtxInfo(-1, -1, -1, -1, -1); RETURN; END IF; IF "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.trace_level >= 1 THEN "FE_GG" .trace_put_line ('DDL', 'Object ID is [' || to_char ("FE_GG" .DDLReplication.currentObjectId) || ']'); "FE_GG" .trace_put_line ('DDLTRACE1', 'Before Trigger: point in execution = [4]' ); END IF; -- In general, history is not required for CREATE DDLs as there can't be -- any DML for an object prior to it being created. This also -- eliminates the problem of objects that don't exist in the context -- of ddl trigger, since this is before ddl trigge r. Any CREATE DDL -- suffers from that issue. -- For CREATE INDEX DDLs take history as the key sey may change as -- a result of the DDL (bug 14032266). IF (ora_sysevent <> 'CREATE' OR (toIgnore = 'NO' AND real_ora_dict_obj_type = 'INDEX' AND otype = 'TABLE')) THEN "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.beginHistory (); IF real_ora_dict_obj_type = 'SEQUENCE' THEN /* For sequences, we need sequence object id, name and rowid for the most part in order to map rowid to objectid/name As sequences don't have properties as tables, this is where we must stop gathering metadata as well */ IF "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.trace_level >= 1 THEN "FE_GG" .trace_put_line ('DDLTRACE1', 'Before Trigger: point in execution = [4-seq], sequence cache [' || to_char (seqCache) || '], sequence incrementby [' || to_char (seqInc rementBy) || ']' ); END IF; "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.getTableInfo ( "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.ddlBaseObjNum, real_ora_dict_obj_name, real_ora_dict_obj_owner, real_ora_dict_obj_type, ora_sysevent, to_char(currUserId), "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.currentMasterOwner, "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.currentMasterName, substr (stmt, 1, 4000 - 10), toIgnore, isTypeTable); "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.getColDefs ( "FE_GG".DDLReplication.ddlBaseObjNum, real_ora_dict_obj_owner, real_ora_dict_obj_name); IF "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.useAllKeys = 1 THEN "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.getKeyColsUseAllKeys ( "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.ddlBaseObjNum, real_ora_dict_obj_owner, real_ora_dict_obj_name); END IF; -- end inserting metadata to history /* END HISTORY table inserts */ END IF; /* make sure endHistory record is placed for sequences too */ "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.endHistory (); END IF; BEGIN IF 'FALSE' = 'TRUE' OR 'FALSE' = 'TRUE' THEN "FE_GG" .trace_put_line ('DDLTRACE1', 'Trigger: Raising simulated 1013 error'); RAISE userCancelSimulate; END IF; EXCEPTION WHEN OTHERS THEN IF instr ("FE_GG" .DDLRepl ication.raisable_errors, to_char (SQLCODE, 'S00000')) > 0 THEN RAISE; END IF; IF 'FALSE' = 'TRUE' THEN "FE_GG" .trace_put_line ('DDLTRACE1', 'Trigger: Raising simulated nested 1013 error'); END IF; -- EXCEPTIONS -- handle exceptions (if so specified) IF "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.trace_level >= 0 THEN "FE_GG" .trace_put_line ('DDL', '------------------------- End of log for DDL sequence [' || to_char ("FE_GG" .DDLReplication.currentDDLSeq) || ']'); END IF; IF "FE_GG" .DDLRep lication.sql_trace = 1 THEN dbms_session.set_sql_trace(false); END IF; "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.setCtxInfo(-1, -1, -1, -1, -1); RETURN; EXCEPTION WHEN OTHERS THEN IF instr ("FE_GG" .DDLReplication.raisable_errors, to_char (SQLCODE, 'S00000')) > 0 THEN RAISE; END IF; "FE_GG" .trace_put_line ('DDL', 'Trigger sys.' || 'GGS_DDL_TRIGGER_BEFORE' || ' :Error processing DDL operation [' || stmt || '], error ' || SQLERRM || ', error stack: ' || "FE_GG" .ddlora_getErrorStack); -- this code will delete any previous garbage from marker data so if trigger commits, nothing is there -- unless we put it down here somewhere (in big trigger exception) or in size handling above -- this way extract doesn't abend from interrupted garbage -- note that this really shouldn't happen (it does when simulated) because oracle actually roll sback transaction IF "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.currentMarkerSeq IS NOT NULL THEN -- only if marker seqno set BEGIN "FE_GG" .trace_put_line ('DDL', 'Cleaning up marker sequence [' || "FE_GG" .DDLReplication.currentMarkerSeq || ']'); Finding 1: Top SQL Statements
Impact is .72 active sessions, 87.09% of total activity.

SQL statements consuming significant database time were found. These
statements offer a good opportunity for performance improvement.

   Estimated benefit is .37 active sessions, 44.7% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------

      "8dz2xt4gcf0y0".

Finding 2: Undersized SGA
Impact is .15 active sessions, 17.87% of total activity.
--------------------------------------------------------
The SGA was inadequately sized, causing additional I/O or hard parses.
The value of parameter "sga_target" was "10240 M" during the analysis period.

   Recommendation 1: Database Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .07 active sessions, 8.94% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Increase the size of the SGA by setting the parameter "sga_target" to
      11520 M.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "User I/O" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is .2 active sessions, 24.18% of total activity.


Finding 3: Top Segments by "User I/O" and "Cluster"
Impact is .14 active sessions, 16.67% of total activity.
--------------------------------------------------------
Individual database segments responsible for significant "User I/O" and
"Cluster" waits were found.

   Recommendation 1: Segment Tuning
